    <text>
        <body>
            <head>1. Telegram From the Embassy in <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisia</placeName> to the Department of State<note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d1fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign
                    Policy File, D770011–0832. Secret; <gloss target="#t_Exdis_1">Exdis</gloss>.
                    Sent for information to Algiers, Cairo, Moscow, and Tripoli.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Tunis</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1977-01-12T10:43:00+00:00">January 12, 1977, 1043Z</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>252. Dept pls pass <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recjQ97iMHKp6vwlA">DOD</orgName>
                </gloss>. Subject: Alleged <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName>
                Decision To “Unite” <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> and
                    <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>.</p>
            <p>1. Admiral <persName corresp="recfzHdbhyuraVPCp">Bagley</persName>, <gloss
                    target="#t_CINCUSNAVEUR_1">CINCUSNAVEUR</gloss>, was received by <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisian</placeName> Minister of Defense <persName
                    corresp="rec5Sv0J35C9SayIb">Farhat</persName> on January 11, shortly after his
                arrival in <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName> on official
                visit. Atmosphere was cordial and meeting served useful purposes.</p>
            <p>2. It was obvious throughout meeting that <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libya</placeName> still uppermost in minds of <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisian</placeName> defense officials (Deputy
                Defense Minister Bennour, Secretary General Alouini and Navy Chief of Staff Jedidi
                also present). <persName corresp="rec5Sv0J35C9SayIb">Farhat</persName> stated during
                meeting that new source of concern was intelligence report received by <gloss
                    target="#t_GOT_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">GOT</placeName>
                </gloss> concerning secret meeting held by <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU"
                    >Qadhafi</persName> on approximately January 1 in which he allegedly outlined
                his plans for “uniting” with <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj"
                    >Tunisia</placeName>. <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName>
                supposedly told meeting that while in Moscow he had obtained assurances that if he
                decided to “take over” <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>,
                Moscow would maintain hands off policy (i.e. would not object to <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> use of <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> arms for this purpose). <persName
                    corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> went on to say that he had made
                definite decision to unify <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>
                and <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName> by any means,
                including force, and that he believed he could count on <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> support or neutrality in the
                event he attaked <placeName corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>.</p>
            <p>3. <persName corresp="rec5Sv0J35C9SayIb">Farhat</persName> said he took reported
                    <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> remarks seriously. He
                believed that <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> had decided
                that <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> was more than he could
                chew and that he would now turn his attention to <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>. <persName
                    corresp="rec5Sv0J35C9SayIb">Farhat</persName> said he believed <persName
                    corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> counting on Egyptian, Iraqi and
                    <placeName corresp="recuO0BsDEvql1RNC">Palestinian</placeName> mercenaries, whom
                he now recruiting, to make up for lack of trained <pb facs="0023" n="2"
                    xml:id="pg_2"/> Libyans. <persName corresp="rec5Sv0J35C9SayIb">Farhat</persName>
                added that in event of hostilities he expected <placeName
                    corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> would both remain neutral.</p>
            <p>4. Questioned further at dinner that evening about seriousness of reported <persName
                    corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> threat, Bennour said it “very
                disturbing” fresh intelligence acquired only “three or four days ago”.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName>
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">King</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
